abstract: TANGIER, June 3.--M.L. Ordega, the French Minister to Morocco, has returned from his visit to Paris. A friendly reception was accorded him. Several tribes came from the interior to pay their respects. The Mussulmans display a strong feeling in favor of France. The tribes are rallying about the Cherif of Wazan. It is stated in Tangier that a movement is on foot throughout Morocco which is likely to lead to results altogether unforeseen.

abstract: So the story goes, that Moliere once read one of his plays to his serving woman. By her appreciation of it the great writer of comedies was to judge of the excellence of his work. Perhaps the nationality of that housekeeper, for she must have been a Frenchwoman, might have rendered her appreciative. Still, it was a dangerous thing to do, for masters who are authors rarely brook adverse criticisms on the part of dependents.

abstract: "All the world," remarked Cassius, rolling a cigarette, "is at enmity with the lean man. He it is against whom the hand of every man is turned. abstract: PITTSBURG, June 12.--The races were continued here to-day. The weather was warm, the track fast, and the attendance good. The first race was for a purse of $400, of which $50 to the second; one mile. Starters: General Harding, (Bryant,) Boatman, (Withers,) Bouquet, (Miller.) Betting--General Harding, $100; the field, $25. General Harding won in a gallop by a length, with Boatman second and Bouquet a very bad third. Time--1:45. French pools paid $6.80.

abstract: WASHINGTON, June 18.--The Utah bill was passed in the Senate to-day by a vote of 33 to 15. The bill, as finally passed, provides that the lawful husband or wife may be compelled to testify in prosecutions for bigamy, polygamy, or unlawful cohabitation. abstract: WAVERLY, Tenn., June 28.--William H. Owens to-day shot and killed Wilson Larkin. Larkin had associated his own name in an indecent manner with Owens's wife, and an altercation arose between the two men. Owens got a gun, when Larkin ran away. Owens afterward, on his way home, was followed by Larkin with a navy pistol, threatening to kill him. Owens thereupon fired, killing Larkin instantly. The Coroner's verdict was justifiable homicide.

abstract: COHOES, N.Y., June 29.--St. Agnes's Church, at this place, J.F. Lowery, Pastor, was consecrated to-day by Bishop McNierny. The odifice was crowded and several visiting clergymen were present. Only one other church in this diocese, that at Syracuse, is free from debt.
